
# Phase 1 - Install Ollama

## Step 1: Download Ollama

Go to:

**[https://ollama.com/download](https://ollama.com/download)**

Download the Windows version.

Install it like any normal application.

---

## Step 2: Verify installation

Open **Command Prompt** or **PowerShell**.

Run:

```bash
ollama --version
```

Expected output:

```text
ollama version 0.xx.x
```

Then run:

```bash
ollama
```

You should see the available commands.

---

# Step 3 - Start Ollama

Run:

```bash
ollama serve
```

If it's already running, you may see:

```text
Error: listen tcp 127.0.0.1:11434: address already in use
```

That's actually good—it means the Ollama service is already running.

---

# Step 4 - Test the server

Open a browser:

```
http://localhost:11434
```

You should see:

```text
Ollama is running
```

---

# Phase 2 - Install a coding model

For your PC, I recommend:

```bash
ollama pull qwen2.5-coder:7b
```

This downloads about **4–5 GB**.

Be patient; it may take several minutes.

---

When it finishes, verify the model is installed:

```bash
ollama list
```

Expected output:

```text
NAME
qwen2.5-coder:7b
```

---

# Phase 3 - Chat with the model

Run:

```bash
ollama run qwen2.5-coder:7b
```

You'll enter an interactive chat.

Ask:

```text
Write a Playwright TypeScript test that opens https://example.com and verifies the title.
```

The model should respond with code similar to:

```typescript
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('Example', async ({ page }) => {
    await page.goto('https://example.com');
    await expect(page).toHaveTitle(/Example/);
});
```

Congratulations—you now have a local AI coding assistant.

---

# Phase 4 - Create a Playwright project

Create a new folder:

```text
ollama-playwright
```

Open it in VS Code.

Open a terminal there.

Run:

```bash
npm init -y
```

Then install Playwright:

```bash
npm init playwright@latest
```

Choose:

```text
TypeScript ✔

Tests folder ✔

GitHub Actions ❌

Install Browsers ✔
```

---

Run the sample test:

```bash
npx playwright test
```

It should pass.

---

# Phase 5 - Ask Ollama to generate a real test

Example prompt:

```text
Generate a Playwright TypeScript test.

Website:
https://opensource-demo.orangehrmlive.com/

Scenario:

Login

Username:
Admin

Password:
admin123

Verify dashboard opens.

Use Playwright best practices.
```

Copy the generated code into:

```text
tests/login.spec.ts
```

Run:

```bash
npx playwright test
```

If successful, view the HTML report:

```bash
npx playwright show-report
```

---

# Phase 6 - Automate the prompt

Instead of using the chat interface, create a file named `generate.js`:

```javascript
const axios = require("axios");

const prompt = `
Generate a Playwright TypeScript test.

Website:
https://example.com

Scenario:
Login
`;

axios.post("http://localhost:11434/api/generate", {
    model: "qwen2.5-coder:7b",
    prompt: prompt,
    stream: false
}).then(res => {
    console.log(res.data.response);
});
```

Install Axios:

```bash
npm install axios
```

Run:

```bash
node generate.js
```

You should see the generated Playwright code printed in the terminal.

This is the same API your future backend will call.

---

# Phase 7 - Save the generated test automatically

Instead of printing the response, save it:

```javascript
const fs = require('fs');

fs.writeFileSync(
    'tests/generated.spec.ts',
    res.data.response
);
```

Now every AI response becomes a Playwright test file automatically.

---

# Phase 8 - Execute Playwright automatically

Run:

```bash
npx playwright test tests/generated.spec.ts
```

or from Node.js:

```javascript
const { exec } = require("child_process");

exec("npx playwright test", (err, stdout, stderr) => {
    console.log(stdout);
});
```

